node.text:
There have been multiple times this year (this month, even) where I’ve asked myself, “why does this feel so hard? Why is it so hard? Why do I feel so (blank)?”

It’s so easy to assume things feel hard because *we* are doing something wrong, because *we* aren’t doing enough, because *we* are having an irrational response.

But sometimes, things feel hard because they ARE hard.
Sometimes, things feel difficult because difficult things are happening.
Sometimes, life feels challenging because life holds challenges.

What if we let go of holding responsibility for always feeling ease and instead, gave ourselves permission to respond in ways that are deeply understandable and valid?
What if we let go of impossible standards and instead allowed ourselves to soften into whatever arises in the moment?
What if we let go of assuming we’re supposed to feel ease and goodness constantly, and instead let ourselves fully be with the truth of what’s within us at any given time?

How might this actually support us in re-centering ease?
How might this actually help us tap into what we need?
How might this actually remind us of our adaptability and capacity to be with the full range of our human experience?

Life is hard.
Life is challenging.
Life is difficult.
We get to be human.
We get to be complex.
We get to be more than one thing.

Our worth and goodness isn’t in how positive we are, how well we take care of ourselves, or how perfectly we respond to difficulty.
We are not better or worse based on how easy or hard the world is for us, now or ever.
Our worth and goodness just is.
Now what?
🕊️

node.title: Sometimes, things are hard because they're hard.

I'm sharing a bit about how we're already good, without the need to constantly become better/bigger/faster/smarter/(blank). It's hard to believe in a culture that makes us feel like there's always something to fix or change about ourselves, yet when we change from a place of wholeness instead of a place of lack, we give ourselves the chance to live into who we truly are.

Thank you for being here, as always. I'm thinking of you and I hope you're taking good care. 🤍

A few reminders on themes I've been witnessing often these past few weeks. It can be really helpful to hear these things from a human's voice instead of quickly glancing at a post. I hope this serves as a mirror of the fact that you are doing great, no matter how you're doing. We will each inherently have our own individual experiences amongst this collective experience, and honoring that is a huge act of self-compassion.

Thank you, as always, for being here. Your feedback and connection has been a true light during this time, and I feel so grateful to get to share with you and learn alongside you. Take good care, friends. 💛

node.text:
Some of the stories I told myself before sharing this: No one wants to see me on video. No one wants to hear me talk. I'm more valuable when I provide tangible tools than when I share from my heart. I should make sure my videos are more professional or put-together. I should re-record without sharing how nervous it makes me. And then a story about how I shouldn't share all these stories that arose! Our brains (even the most trained and resourced brains) are wild.

These stories aren't true and they hold me back from connecting from the truth of who I am, so sharing video here is a small way of dismantling these stories and showing up in my wholeness. It's a reminder that we can all show up for ourselves in ways that aren't comfy but lead to growth. A reminder that we don't always need to wait until we're "ready" to take action. A reminder that we can think a thought and choose to believe it or not. A way of allowing you to hear from someone else's voice that you get to choose what you tell yourself, what you cultivate, and what you release. And, it's a way of breaking up consumption culture and creating space to pause and check in with yourself for more than a fleeting second.

We so often forget that we are not our stories and we don't need to live them out if they aren't serving us or allowing our truth to surface. I hope this letter from my heart to yours is a reminder to question your thoughts and remember what's underneath. You are already good, whole, and enough. We all are. 💫

node.text:
Sometimes, we don’t need advice, reminders, or tools. We don’t always need another quote or another list of things to try or another inspiring story. We don’t always want more information to consume — especially during times where the world feels like a lot. Sometimes, what we need is to actually *practice* something that eases our minds and hearts - something other than saving another Instagram post.

Today, I'm sorting through photos to print from a recent trip, bringing my body back there internally, and remembering what is held in the world. These spaces hold within them memories that invoke aliveness, beauty that is difficult to even comprehend, and awe & wonder at what exists around us, even in moments we can’t access it or in times we forget.

When my body feels tense or activated, I sometimes close my eyes and envision these places and spaces. I think about who I was with, the feelings I experienced while witnessing them, the sensation of the fresh air on my skin, the sounds of nothing or wind or wild animals roaming, the magnificence that pierced right through me and the sheer expansiveness that is available to us when we honor our surroundings. I imagine the land underneath my feet, the earth holding me and the sense of connectedness that is possible when we remember it to be so. I let my body remember.

The world can be overwhelming to navigate. It is easy to fall into despair, to be overtaken by grief, and to be unsure of how to process everything being thrown at us. These emotional experiences make so much sense. But when I look at these photos and internally time travel to other times, other places, other memories and other possibilities, I remember to breathe again. I remember to honor why it feels so hard. It's hard because we love.

Grief happens because something mattered to us. These places matter. Possibility matters. Sitting with all of it when we can and honoring ourselves when we can’t matters. May we visit spaces that bring us a sense of resolve and peace when needed -- even if only through photographs. May we return to these understandings when needed -- even if only for a moment.

Sending each of you my love. Take good care. 💛✨💫

node.text:
What something do I have capacity for?
What something feels aligned?
What something am I meant to offer?
What something do I have in me right now?
What something honors what I need to receive and what I have to give?
What something feels doable?
What something doesn't hijack my nervous system?
What something would be most nourishing?
What something is a requirement?
What something is extra?
What something is within my reach in this specific context, moment, and space?

Words I repeat to myself often, in so many scenarios/situations/experiences/moments:

I cannot do everything.
I cannot do it all.
And,
I can do something.

'Something' moves us out of all-or-nothing thinking.
'Something' keeps us accountable to our own bandwidth.
'Something' honors the moment.
'Something' has to be enough sometimes.

Your something will be different than my something will be different than their something. Something can be as small as getting a sip of water or feeding your child; it can be as big as the moon; what matters is checking in with what we have and what we need, and moving accordingly.

Take good care. 🙏🏻

node.text:
Do you ever give time and space to explore what you're wanting to commit to in this season? In this time? In this space you're currently in?

It can be such an illuminating and nourishing practice... to remember we get to choose what we're committed to. To name it and claim it as such. To give ourselves permission for our commitments to be ever-changing, just as we are. To get to the layers underneath the layers and dig into the realness of what we're choosing. To really let ourselves look at the places we don't always want to look and ask, "what is here for me? What is there to be gleaned here? How might this be transformed? Can I be honest with myself? Really honest?"

You may resonate with some of these commitments/soul maps/practices -- or you may have wildly different commitments of your own. Whatever it looks like for you, here's an invitation to take a moment, muse on it, and honor it... whatever it is you find. We can gift this to ourselves and, in turn, to our wider communities and world. ✨💫

Ps. As always, this is an ongoing practice that we will never be perfect at. Perfect isn't the point. A destination isn't the point. Figuring it out isn't the point. Living it moment to moment in all the ways we're able to, over and over, might be. 💫

node.text:
Taking in the power of knowing this deep, already-sacred bond and inherent connection isn't going anywhere. As an adoptee, taking in this power is overwhelming in all ways. It is tender and healing, natural and unbearably real. As a human, it is just magic. I am creating the end of one generational pattern and the beginning of another, literally weaving a new way within me as I write this, and it reminds me of what true, expansive, wide-open possibility feels like. May we all know what it is to grow possibility within ourselves, however it may happen. 💫

I wasn't sure if I'd share a photo of this phase here, if I'd publicly share about this part of me at all; as I've grown, I've realized it is impossible to show up without this part of me, and it is an honor to be able to share. It is so personal and sacred, as I know this journey is for many -- and I also know this journey can be hard to witness for so many reasons. I’ve been working on a very special project behind the scenes for the last few years and I am so grateful (and a little nervous) to finally get to share it with you today...

My first book, Already Enough: A Path to Self-Acceptance is available for pre-order now and will be welcomed into the world this January! 😭✨

This book has been a labor of love and one I’ve poured my personal story and professional experience into. It is expansive and spacious, supportive and nurturing, illuminating and insightful. It is my hope that this book will guide you back to your own wisdom, that it will support you in more deeply understanding yourself, and that it will lead you into a more whole, compassionate, and accepting relationship with all parts of who you are. In essence, I hope it offers a mirror that allows you to remember you are, and have always been, enough.

Already Enough came from my own experiences in unraveling the stories I had been living from for so long: stories of not being enough, of not belonging, and of not being worthy. Through understanding, reframing, and integrating the truth of who I am, I’ve been able to re-shape the way I see myself and the world — not perfect, but more whole. I believe we all deserve to live fully into the goodness and beauty of who we are, including the messy, hard parts.

The book will gently guide you through understanding how you’ve come to hold certain stories and beliefs about yourself, through utilizing nourishing practices, mindsets, and ways of being in order to return to who you truly are, and through integrating all parts of you — the messy and the beautiful — to live a more whole, meaningful life.

You can pre-order now and read more about the book through the link in my bio and stories. Pre-orders help new authors so much, and every single one is so deeply appreciated.

I feel so lucky to get to share this work with you and I cannot wait for it to be in your hands. Big thank yous to my editor @emilycgraff, my agent @missmattingly of @presentperfectlit, and every human who has nurtured me through this process. It’s such a dream and a true gift to offer this to the world. 🙏🏻🤍

I long thought I was too ordinary to take up space. Thinking I wasn’t unique or artistic enough, that my creativity wasn’t niche enough, that my wisdom needed to be turned into something entirely new for it to matter or, alternatively, that I needed to become more mainstream and on-trend, that I needed a “stronger” personality or a louder voice, that I’d have to shape-shift myself in order to share the words and work I wanted to share. In essence, I didn’t think I belonged in the spaces I wanted to be in — spaces of creatives, writers, thinkers, healers, and guides I admire.

Over the last nearly four years, I’ve been slowly unzipping that false story and allowing my true self to step out in public here. I’ve been sharing bits and pieces, stretching my capacity to trust that what I have to say matters, engaging my being-witnessed muscles, and slowly learning how to embody my place in the world — my quieter yet still potent place. My softer yet still strong place. My often-simple yet equally-wise place. My not-quite-a-mystic-but-also-probably-a-mystic place. My curious, questioning, deep-thinking-and-feeling place. My dark and light and in-between place. My nuanced, not-so-straightforward place. My widely compassionate place. The place only I can occupy in the world.

What I’ve come to understand in a more full way is that sometimes, just being ourselves in all the ways we are is itself an offering. Even when we feel ordinary or small. Even when we aren’t sure. Even when we’re in the midst of figuring things out. Even while we’re becoming 100 different versions of ourselves. We can trust that even then, who we are and what we have to give and share belongs and is an offering not only to our own essence, but also to all the humans seeking exactly what we have to give in the way only we can give it.

If you, too, have moved from a place of perpetual self-doubt into a place of starting to trust your own gifts in this world, I see you and I honor you. If it’s taken a while, you are right on time. If you’re still in limbo, you’re in the right place. Keep going. Keep trusting. Your essence and energy, exactly as they are, are needed and deeply enough. 🙏🏻🌼✨
